Brett Bowden examines how the idea of civilization has informed our thinking about international relations over the course of ten centuries. From the Crusades to the colonial era to the global war on terror, this sweeping volume exposes “civilization” as a stage-managed account of history that legitimizes imperialism, uniformity, and conformity to Western standards, culminating in a liberal-democratic global order. Along the way, Bowden explores the variety of confrontations and conquests—as well as those peoples and places excluded or swept aside—undertaken in the name of civilization. Concluding that the “West and the rest” have more commonalities than differences,this provocative and engaging bookultimately points the way toward an authentic intercivilizational dialogue that emphasizes cooperation over clashes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCivilizationxHistory. 0aCivilizationxPhilosophy. 0aImperialism. 0aInternational relationsxPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy, European. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aempire, civilization, race, whiteness, imperialism, colonialism, war on terror, religion, history, uniformity, conformity, otherness, globalization, international relations, philosophy, territory, expansion, progress, art, science, modernity, enlightenment, colonization, spain, cosmopolitanism, white mans burden, monetary fund, nation building, military interventions, finance, trade, commerce, nonfiction.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022606814540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226068169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226068169/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruy